{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_01AdTx8EAVWLU6sMcxZz5buC","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All 3 nodes are running and clustered, all 3 pods ready.\n\n## Summary\n\nThe RabbitMQ side was already correctly configured (`rabbitmq_prometheus` plugin enabled, port 15692 listening on `0.0.0.0`). The gap was entirely on the Prometheus side — the `prometheus-config` ConfigMap had no scrape job for RabbitMQ and no `rule_files` directive, so the `prometheus-rules` ConfigMap (defining the `rabbitmq_up` recording rule) was mounted but never loaded.\n\nFix applied (native resources only — just edited the existing ConfigMap, no new controllers/CRDs):\n- Added a `rabbitmq` scrape job to `prometheus-config` with static targets for the 3 pod DNS names via the existing headless service (`rabbitmq-{0,1,2}.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local:15692`, path `/metrics`).\n- Added `rule_files: - /etc/prometheus/rules/*.yml` so the already-mounted `prometheus-rules` ConfigMap actually gets loaded.\n- Reloaded Prometheus via its `/-/reload` endpoint (already exposed via `--web.enable-lifecycle`, no pod restart needed).\n\nVerified:\n- `/api/v1/targets` shows all 3 `rabbitmq` targets with `health: up`.\n- `rabbitmq_up` query returns 3 samples (value `1`).\n- RabbitMQ cluster still shows 3/3 pods running and clustered (`rabbitmqctl cluster_status`)."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":131,"cache_creation_input_tokens":943,"cache_read_input_tokens":53635,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":943},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"36db3c85-67f6-4768-8b94-ef5f75e05a83","uuid":"e30537e3-40a8-44a8-b788-ed9c514ed283","request_id":"req_011CcafYppUPowLB9CXSQgiJ"}
